Condition : 4 - The use and/or development hereby approved shall operate at all times  to meet the following standards:
(i)  	Noise from any plant or machinery shall not exceed 5dB(A) below the existing background noise level when measured at the boundary of the nearest noise-sensitive property;
(ii)  	The ventilation flue discharge point shall be not less than one metre above the highest ridge of the building to which it is attached. (note - Local circumstances, e.g. nearby tall buildings or the proximity of openable windows may dictate that a higher discharge point is necessary to achieve effective dilution and dispersion of cooking odours in the exhausted air and you are advised to contact the Council about this where you think this may be the case);
The termination of the flue shall be plain, with airflow unobstructed by a cowl or rain deflector to maximise the dilution and dispersion of cooking odours.
(iii) 	Air extracted from the food cooking air must pass through a filtration system. In addition, simple grease traps and activated carbon filters (or some other approved odour removal technology) shall be incorporated into the design to minimise the likelihood of cooking odours being present in the exhausted air.;
(iv)  	Flexible couplings and anti-vibration mountings shall be used on all surface mounted plans that generates noise or vibrations to prevent the transmission of noise and vibration into any adjoining property.

Condition : 6 - Notwithstanding any details included in the submitted plans, no part of the development shall first be occupied until details of both hard and soft landscape works have been submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority. These details shall include 
(a)	a statement setting out the design objectives and how these will be delivered; 
(b)	means of enclosure/boundary treatment(s) and retaining structures;
(c)	vehicle parking layouts; 
(d)	other vehicle and pedestrian access and circulation areas;
(e)	hard surfacing materials; 
(f)	planting plans, written specifications (including cultivation and other operations associated with plant and grass establishment); schedules of plants, noting species, plant sizes and proposed numbers and densities where appropriate; and
(g)	an implementation programme (including phasing of work where relevant).
The landscaping works shall comply with the requirements specified in BS 3936 (1992) 'Specification of Nursery Stock Part 1 Trees and Shrubs', and in BS 4428 (1989) 'Recommendations for General Landscape Operations', and shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details before the development hereby permitted is first occupied or brought into use, or such other date(s) as may be specified in the agreed implementation programme.
